The role of government is often a contentious issue. This is especially true in the economic area. What function should government have with respect to economic decisions, and how should it exercise that function?

In “The Use of Knowledge in Society” (1945), economist F.A. Hayek, a libertarian, argued that, due to the complexity of society and the number of relationships that people must take into account when they make decisions, the government should not be given the task of making complex economic decisions. It is impossible for any one individual, or even for any group of individuals, to have all the information necessary to make such decisions effectively. Furthermore, the more decisions that are made at a centralized level, the more “knowledge will be misused and even destroyed in the attempt to centralize too much power in the wrong hands.”^{1}

